# Sasha Palmer — Portfolio Website

A personal portfolio site built to showcase my journey into software development, including my projects, technical skills, and background as an educator transitioning into tech.

🔗 **Live site:** [sasha-tameka.github.io/resume-website](https://sasha-tameka.github.io/resume-website/)

## About

I'm a Software Development graduate based in Montréal, looking to break into the tech industry. Outside of my studies, I work as an educator supporting adults with special needs — experience that's taught me patience, clear communication, and problem-solving under pressure. This site is where I bring my coding work together in one place.

## Features

- **Animated hero section** with a typewriter effect cycling through roles
- **Skills section** — hover-reveal icons for each technology
- **Projects grid** with click-to-expand modals showing project details, demo videos, and links to source code
- **Contact form** powered by EmailJS — sends messages directly from the browser, no backend required
- **Fully responsive** — mobile hamburger navigation and a layout that adapts down to phone-sized screens
- **Downloadable CV** directly from the nav bar

## Built With

- HTML5
- CSS3 (custom properties, Flexbox, Grid, media queries)
- JavaScript (vanilla, no frameworks)
- [EmailJS](https://www.emailjs.com/) — contact form handling
- [Font Awesome](https://fontawesome.com/) — icons
- Google Fonts (Poppins)

## Project Structure

```
resume-website/
├── index.html          # Main page markup
├── style.css           # All styling, including responsive breakpoints
├── script.js           # Typewriter effect, mobile menu, project modals, EmailJS
├── icons/              # Skill icons, profile image, project assets
│   └── videos/         # Project demo clips shown in modals
└── Sasha Palmer revisedcv.pdf
```

## Running Locally

1. Clone the repo:
   ```bash
   git clone https://github.com/Sasha-Tameka/resume-website.git
   ```
2. Open `index.html` directly in your browser, or serve it locally (e.g. with the VS Code "Live Server" extension) for the best experience.

No build step or dependencies needed — it's all static files.

## Deployment

This site is deployed via **GitHub Pages** directly from the `main` branch.

